codex
1. Verdict: freeze-plan

2. Top 3 findings

- category: prevention gap
  why it matters: The template has truth surfaces, but it does not define a mechanical rule for when progress must be reflected into them. That makes `session_state.md` and `ROADMAP.md` optional narrative outputs instead of execution-coupled surfaces.
  smallest honest next step: Add a required execution-sync contract to the task packet and execution contract with three fields only: `progress_unit`, `sync_required_events`, and `state_owner_surfaces`.

- category: detection gap
  why it matters: The current closeout audit catches unsupported completion claims, but it does not detect the more common failure mode: code/tests/receipts move forward while state surfaces stay stale.
  smallest honest next step: Ship a `state_sync_audit.py` validator that compares changed implementation files, task receipts, and a `Last Synced Receipt` field in `session_state.md` and `ROADMAP.md`.

- category: repair gap
  why it matters: Hard-failing drift without a bounded reconciliation path just creates blocked tasks and more stale docs. Imperfect agents need a repair loop, not only a prohibition.
  smallest honest next step: Add a `reconcile-drift` script that either updates the state surfaces from the latest receipt or generates a `drift_packet.md` with explicit contradictions to resolve before closeout.

3. Proposed anti-drift mechanism table

| mechanism | template surface(s) | enforcement level | why this level is honest |
|---|---|---|---|
| Execution-sync contract on every non-trivial task: require `progress_unit`, `sync_required_events`, `state_owner_surfaces`, `task_slug` | validator: extend `scripts/validate_template.py`; scripts/tools: extend task/init generator or `scripts/git_audit_pipeline.py`; runbooks: execution contract and adoption guide | hard-fail | The template can honestly require these fields to exist in task artifacts, even if it cannot force perfect runtime behavior. |
| Structured execution receipt ledger per task, with event types like `code_changed`, `validation_ran`, `scope_changed`, `blocked`, `done` | scripts/tools: new `scripts/execution_state.py emit-receipt`; templates: new receipt template or NDJSON schema under `tmp/execution/<task_slug>/`; runbooks: demo workflow | workflow-only | The template cannot intercept every edit in every client, so receipt emission is strongest when routed through tool wrappers and runbooks, not as a universal hard gate. |
| `Last Synced Receipt` field in `session_state.md` and active `ROADMAP.md` phase, updated when state is reconciled | validator: `state_sync_audit.py`; templates: `templates/session_state.template.md`, `templates/roadmap.template.md`; scripts/tools: reconcile helper | hard-fail | This is mechanically checkable at commit/push/CI time: latest required receipt exists, and truth surfaces point to it or explicitly declare no state impact. |
| Diff-aware drift audit: fail if implementation-scope files or validation receipts changed after the last synced receipt and no reconciliation receipt exists | validator: new `scripts/state_sync_audit.py`; runbooks/pipelines: pre-commit, pre-push, CI | hard-fail | The template can enforce checkpoint integrity at repository boundaries even though it cannot watch the agent continuously. |
| Drift repair loop: generate `tmp/execution/<task_slug>/drift_packet.md` listing unsynced receipts, contradictory claims, and missing surface updates | scripts/tools: `scripts/execution_state.py reconcile-drift`; runbooks: resumable audit pipeline, handoff workflow | repair-loop | Some contradictions need human or agent judgment. The honest move is to force explicit reconciliation before closeout, not guess. |
| Optional wrapper commands for common execution steps so receipts are emitted automatically when adopters use the toolchain | scripts/tools: wrappers for test/lint/task steps; docs: developer toolchain and adoption guide | advisory | This materially reduces drift for adopters who opt in, but it is not universal because many repos and executors will still run raw commands. |
| Handoff gate: ownership change is invalid unless latest receipt is synced or a drift packet exists | validator: audit handoff artifacts; runbooks: resumable handoff pipeline | repair-loop | Ownership transitions are a high-drift moment. The template can require either synchronized state or an explicit repair artifact before handoff. |

Prevention belongs mostly in scripts/tools and templates: execution-sync contract, receipt schema, wrapper commands.
Detection belongs in validator and pipelines: `state_sync_audit.py`, hook/CI checks, contradiction rules.
Repair belongs in scripts/tools plus runbooks: `reconcile-drift`, `drift_packet.md`, handoff rules.

4. Ordered rollout plan

1. Add the minimum state-sync schema: execution-sync contract fields, receipt schema, and `Last Synced Receipt` fields in `session_state.md` and `ROADMAP.md`.
2. Ship `scripts/state_sync_audit.py` and wire it into pre-commit, pre-push, and CI with one initial hard rule: implementation changes or validation receipts require a newer synced receipt reference or an explicit no-impact reconciliation receipt.
3. Add `scripts/execution_state.py` with `emit-receipt`, `reconcile-state`, and `reconcile-drift` commands so the validator has a usable repair path.
4. Update runbooks and demo project to make the workflow concrete: start task, emit receipts during bounded passes, reconcile state before handoff/closeout.
5. Only after the repair path works, add stricter contradiction checks between latest receipt status and roadmap/session claims.

5. One thing the template must explicitly avoid

Do not claim “every meaningful action will automatically update `session_state.md` and `ROADMAP.md` in real time”; the template does not control all executors or commands, so the honest contract is checkpoint enforcement plus repair, not full runtime orchestration.

6. Final recommendation in one sentence

Freeze a combined B+C+D plan: make progress event receipts the source for mid-task detection, require truth surfaces to point at the latest synced receipt at repository checkpoints, and force drift into an explicit reconciliation loop instead of trusting prose discipline.
